          "warning_signs": "Warning Signs",
          "warning_signs_description":
              "\u2022 Bleeding\n\u2022 Severe nausea and vomiting\n\u2022 A marked decline in fetal activity.\n\u2022 Contractions occurring at the beginning of the 3rd trimester.\n\u2022 Water breaking\n\u2022 Severe headache, severe abdominal pain, visual disturbances, and swelling during the 3rd trimester.\n\u2022 Flu-like symptoms\n\u2022 Hyperthermia\n\u2022 No increase in weight or abnormal increase in weight.\nIf you experience any of these signs and symptoms, notify your healthcare provider immediately or present to the emergency room.",
          "preeclampsia_eclampsia": "Preeclampsia and Eclampsia",
          "preeclampsia_eclampsia_description":
              "Preeclampsia: A pregnancy complication that can affect some women during the 2nd or 3rd trimesters. It is characterized by blood pressure high enough to pose a risk on the mother and the fetus. Symptoms of preeclampsia include:\n\u2022 Sudden weight gain\n\u2022 Headache\n\u2022 Vision changes (blurred)\n\u2022 Abnormal fluid retention, especially in the hands, face, and around the eyes\n\u2022 Sudden nausea and vomiting – note that these two symptoms are uncommon during the second and third trimesters.\n\u2022 Proteinurea (elevated protein levels in the urine)\nIf you are experiencing any of these signs or symptoms, call your doctor immediately and ask for a same day appointment.\nOther symptoms of preeclampsia include:\n\u2022 Lower back pain, shoulder pain, and abdominal pain\n\u2022 Anxiety\n\u2022 Shortness of breath\nSometimes, the only sign manifested in preeclampsia is elevated blood pressure, which can usually go unfelt. That is why routine doctor’s visits are important, during which weight, blood pressure, and urine protein levels are monitored. Home blood pressure monitoring is highly recommended as well. Blood pressure is best measured at the same position (sitting or lying) and at the same time every day. You can test your pressure at home.\nEclampsia: a life-threatening complication which usually follows preeclampsia, in which seizure attacks and loss of consciousness occur, sometimes life threatening for both mother and fetus. The doctor should be contacted immediately in such an event.\nRoutine doctor visits are very important throughout pregnancy to check for the risk of any such complications, which may be prevented by early medical treatment.",
          "constipation": "Constipation",
          "constipation_description":
              "Constipation is a common complication of pregnancy, especially during the later stages. Here are a few tips for managing constipation:\n\u2022 Increase your intake of fluids like water and fruit juices, such as orange, apple, and watermelon fruit. This promotes bowel movement.\n\u2022 Daily exercise and physical activity are efficient in preventing constipation.\n\u2022 Increase your fiber intake with fiber-rich foods such as vegetables, legumes, fruits, and whole-grain products like brown bread, corn, and oats. Talk to your doctor about taking fiber supplements.",
          "leg_cramps": "Leg Cramps",
          "leg_cramps_description":
              "Cramps are involuntary and painful muscle twitching mostly affecting the legs, feet, or both. They can occur as sudden attacks during sleep, especially during the second and third trimesters. Although the cause behind them is unknown, the following tips are helpful in preventing them:\n\u2022 Extend your legs before going to sleep.\n\u2022 Stay physically active. Physical activity helps to prevent cramps during pregnancy. However, seek your doctor’s permission before starting an exercise program.\n\u2022 Take magnesium supplements. Some studies recommend magnesium supplementation as a preventive measure.\n\u2022 Select comfortable shoes that provide the necessary support to your feet.\n\u2022 In the event of a leg cramp, extend your leg, raise it to an elevated position and maintain it there.\n\u2022 A warm compress or warm bath can also help.",
          "acidity_heartburn": "Acidity and Heartburn",
          "acidity_heartburn_description":
              "Acidity and heartburn is one of the most disturbing symptoms a pregnant woman can experience, especially during the later stages of pregnancy. The growth in the size of the uterus due to the developing fetus causes more pressure on the stomach, resulting in a flow-back of stomach acids into the esophagus. The elevated progesterone levels as well lead to the relaxation of the esophageal sphincter, allowing the stomach contents back up into the esophagus, thereby causing heartburn. However, this complication will disappear after birth.\nTips for preventing and minimizing heartburn:\n\u2022 Chew your food well and slowly.\n\u2022 Avoid meals high in fat such as fast food meals.\n\u2022 Avoid overloading your stomach. Eat smaller and more frequent meals rather than larger and less frequent ones.\n\u2022 Avoid heavy meals for at least three hours before going to bed.\n\u2022 Avoid caffeinated beverages such as coffee and tea.\n\u2022 Avoid excessive weight gain (normal weight gain during pregnancy ranges from 11.5 to 18 kg if weight was normal before pregnancy).\n\u2022 Do not stretch and sit down immediately after eating.\n\u2022 Wear loose fitted clothes to avoid pressure on your stomach.\n\u2022 If you think you need acid reflux medication, consult your doctor.",
          "varicose_veins": "Varicose Veins",
          "varicose_veins_description":
              "Varicose veins emerge as visible green, purple, or sometimes pink veins on the legs. These veins are swollen and painful, especially after standing for long periods. Varicose veins are one of the most common pregnancy complications seen in up to 40% of pregnant women. The rise in progesterone and the increase in blood volume weaken the blood vessel walls and impose more pressure on the veins pumping the blood to the heart from the lower body. These factors, combined with genetic factors, play a role in the development of varicose veins. Symptoms include fatigue, heavy leg sensation, and some cramping. Varicose veins usually disappear after birth when the venous pressure decreases and when the weight drops. The veins thus return to their original form prior to pregnancy.\nTips to avoid or minimize varicose veins:\n\u2022 Do not stand for long periods. Take breaks whenever possible.\n\u2022 Exercise and walk daily. Elevate your legs daily for 15 minutes at every opportunity.\n\u2022 Avoid excessive weight gain.\n\u2022 Wear compression stockings. Be sure to pick your right size.\n\u2022 Sleep on your left side (the inferior vena cava is located on the right side of your heart).\n\u2022 Do not cross your legs.\n\u2022 Wear loose clothing.\nIf symptoms persist or if the varicose veins are painful, consult your doctor.",
          "morning_sickness": "Morning Sickness",
          "morning_sickness_description":
              "Morning sickness is one of the most common symptoms affecting 80% of pregnant women, especially during the early stages. Unlike what the name may imply, morning sickness can occur at any time during the day, especially when blood sugar levels are low. Usually, it manifests between the 4th and the 6th week of pregnancy and disappears between the 14th and the 16th weeks, with a possibility of extending for longer periods.\nTips for avoiding morning sickness:\n\u2022 Get enough sleep and rest.\n\u2022 To get out of bed, sit on the edge of your bed for a few minutes before getting up.\n\u2022 Eat crackers or saltines when you wake up in the morning, even before getting out of bed.\n\u2022 Avoid foods and smells that can trigger the nausea.\n\u2022 Eating mustard can be helpful.\n\u2022 Increase your fluid intake.\n\u2022 Eat small and frequent meals.\n\u2022 Eat multiple small meals (instead of small and big meals) that equal the same health benefits of big meals.\n\u2022 Avoid eating junk and fried food.",
          "back_pain": "Back Pain",
          "back_pain_description":
              "Back pain is a common problem that is caused not only by weight gain, but also by the resulting shift in the center of gravity relative to your body. Back pain also results from hormonal changes that cause relaxation of the pelvic and vertebral ligaments. Here are some tips for preventing or minimizing back pain:\n\u2022 Maintain a good posture\n1. Standing posture:\nAs your fetus grows in your womb, your gravity center shifts forward. You will tend to draw yourself backward to maintain your balance. This can strain your lower back muscles and result in pain. To maintain a proper standing posture:\n\u2022 Stand tall and straight.\n\u2022 Keep your chest elevated.\n\u2022 Keep your shoulders relaxed and towards the back.\n\u2022 Keep your feet apart. A wide stance is more supportive. When standing for long periods, allow your feet to relax one at a time by alternating them.\n2. Seating posture:\n\u2022 Choose a chair that supports your back, or place a pillow behind your lower back.\n\u2022 Keep your back straight while seated.\n\u2022 Keep your chest elevated.\n\u2022 Keep your knees apart to allow a comfortable position, while maintaining the soles of your feet on the ground.\n\u2022 To turn, turn your whole body, using your legs for support.\n\u2022 Do not cross your legs.\n\u2022 Choose proper shoes: with low heels, but not flat. These provide better back support.\n\u2022 A maternity support belt can offer good back support.\n\u2022 Carry loads properly: Instead of bending your back or bending from your waist, use your feet and squat while keeping your back straight and using your thigh muscles for support. Limit the loads you carry, and ask for help when needed.\n\u2022 Sleep on your left side. Do not sleep on your back. You can bend your knees and place a pillow between them and behind your back.\n\u2022 A massage, a heating pad, or an ice pack can soothe the pain.\n\u2022 Daily exercise helps to strengthen your back and reduce the pain during pregnancy. Ask your doctor about which exercises are appropriate for you. Light workouts such as walking and water exercises are good options. Lower back exercises, as illustrated below, are also a good example.\nStart by placing your hands and knees on the floor, while keeping your head aligned with your flat back. Then, tuck your belly in and slightly bend your back. Remain in this position for a few seconds, and then relax while maintaining your back as straight as possible. With practice, you will gradually be able to repeat this exercise as many as ten times in a row.\n\u2022 Complementary therapy, such as acupuncture, may help in reducing back pain. However, talk to your doctor before getting started.\n\u2022 If your back pain persists for over a week, ask your doctor which pain medicine that is right for you. Keep in mind that back pain can be a sign of early labor (or early delivery). Back pain along with vaginal bleeding, fever, or urinary burning can be a sign of a medical emergency. If you are concerned about your back pain, do not hesitate to talk to your doctor.",
          "headache": "Headache",
          "headache_description":
              "Headache is a common symptom during pregnancy. Although the exact cause is not yet known, hormonal changes and increased blood volume during pregnancy are thought to be some of the reasons behind. More intense headaches have been noticed in women who suffered headaches more regularly prior to pregnancy. Tips to avoid headaches:\n\u2022 Stay aware of and avoid any possible triggers to headache in your lifestyle and diet.\n\u2022 Gradually incorporate moderate physical activity into your daily lifestyle such as walking and aerobic exercise.\n\u2022 Apply relaxation techniques for stress management:\n\u2022\u2022 Exercise deep breathing and Yoga.\n\u2022\u2022 Learn how to cope with stress triggering factors.\n\u2022\u2022 Spend quality time with friends who can cheer you up, and engage in activities in which you find pleasure.\n\u2022\u2022 Eat smaller and more frequent meals, and follow a regular meal schedule to maintain your blood sugar levels within normal and prevent rises that might trigger headaches.\n\u2022\u2022 Increase your fluid intake to feel better and healthier.\n\u2022\u2022 Maintain a regular sleep schedule and get enough sleep. Sleep deficiency can trigger a headache.\nIn the event of a headache:\n\u2022 Relax in a dark room with your eyes closed.\n\u2022 Apply a warm compressing band to your head and face, and a cold band on the back of your neck.\n\u2022 Massage your neck and shoulders to help soothe the pain.\nIf these techniques are not helpful, consult your doctor about which pain medicine is right for you.",
          "true_false_labor": "True and False Labor",
          "true_false_labor_description":
              "How to differentiate between true labor and false labor? Keep in mind that not all contractions are a sign of labor. False contractions, also called Braxton Hicks, can be felt as early as the second trimester. The following table can help you differentiate between true and false contractions.\n\nTrue Labor Contractions\tFalse Labor (Braxton Hicks) Contractions\nFelt in the belly and radiate to the lower back, or are felt in the lower back and radiate to the belly.\tFelt in the lower belly.\nRegular.\tIrregular.\nExceed 5 per hour, increase with time, and occur every five to ten minutes.\tDo not increase with time.\nUsually intense and painful, strong enough to trigger labor.\tUsually mild, not strong enough to trigger labor.\nLast for 30 seconds at onset, and increase gradually up to 60 seconds.\tVary in length.\nSometimes accompanied with vaginal discharge or change in the vaginal discharge, bleeding, or flu-like symptoms.\tNot accompanied by any of the mentioned symptoms.\nPressure on the pelvic area.\tNo pressure on the pelvic area.\nDo not stop as you move or change your position.\tUsually stop as you move or change your position.\nTrue contractions can lead to preterm labor if they occur three weeks or earlier before your due date. If you notice any of the true labor contractions, or if you are in doubt, contact your healthcare provider immediately.\nTo ease false contractions:\n\u2022 Try changing your position or activity. Rest if you are walking or standing, or get up and walk if you are sitting at rest.\n\u2022 Apply some relaxation techniques. Take a warm bath (avoid hot baths!), rest or take a nap, or get a massage.\n\u2022 Drink a large glass of water.",
