              "That is right! Week 1 starts with the very first day of your last menstrual period. Since it is hard for your doctor to figure that exact day when you ovulated, or when the sperm and the egg have met in your fallopian tube, he will count your gestational weeks starting from the first day of your last menstrual period. Ovulation will take place roughly two weeks afterwards, when the egg released by your ovary will travel to your fallopian tube, and wait to be fertilized by the sperm. When this happens, you are already two weeks into pregnancy!",
          "fetus_content_w3":
              "The egg and the sperm unite in one of your fallopian tubes to form a zygote.\nIf more than one egg is released, they will be fertilized by the sperm and there will be more than one zygote.\nA zygote contains 46 chromosomes, of which half come from the father, and half come from you.\nThese chromosomes are responsible for defining your fetus’s characteristics such as gender, eye and hair color, some personality traits, and level of intelligence.\nShortly afterwards, the zygote moves down your fallopian tube towards your womb.\nAt this time, the zygote starts to rapidly divide into cell clusters through a process called mitosis.\nThe zygote has now taken the shape of a ball of cells called a blastocyte.\nThe blastocyte is composed of two layers of cells: the inner layer that will develop into an embryo, and an outer layer that will develop into the placenta which will provide the embryo (and later the fetus) with oxygen and nutrients.\nThe outer layer penetrates into the wall of the uterus through a process called implantation.",
          "fetus_content_w4":
              "The brain, the spinal cord, the heart, and all the other organs begin to form during this week.\nThree separate layers have developed now in your embryo:\nThe outer layer, or the ectoderm, which will develop into the skin, the hair, the eyes, the inner ear, and the nervous system.\nThe middle layer, or the mesoderm, which will develop into the heart, the bones, the muscles, the kidneys, and the sex organs.\nThe inner layer, or the endoderm, which will develop into a simple tube covered with a mucous layer, from which the lungs, the intestines, and the bladder will form.\nBy the end of this week, your fetus will reach the size of a pencil tip.",
          "fetus_content_w5":
              "Your fetus continues to grow rapidly this week. The neural tube, from which the brain and the spinal cord form, will close, and the heart divide into chambers and will begin to pump blood. The main facial features of your fetus will start to appear – such as the depressions that will form the inner ears and the arcs that will shape into the lower jaw. Tiny buds that will soon form the arms and legs will sprout, and your fetus will start to take a C shape.",
          "fetus_content_w6":
              "Your fetus’s brain and face develop rapidly.\nThe nostrils and the eye lenses will begin to appear.\nThe shell-like sections of your fetus’s ear will start to shape.\nHis eyes will appear distinct, his upper lip and the tip of his nose are formed, and his curved trunk will begin to straighten.\nYour fetus’s heart will begin to beat and his blood will begin to circulate; however, the heartbeats will still be inaudible at this stage.\nThe four tiny buds that sprouted last week will start to develop a paddle shape.\nYou may start to experience fatigue, breast soreness, and morning sickness.\nThe risk of miscarriage is at its highest at this stage of pregnancy; therefore, you must avoid exhaustion and minimize your coffee consumption or quit smoking if you smoke.\nSigns and symptoms of miscarriage:\n* Severe cramping\n* Vaginal bleeding\n* Green or pink-colored vaginal discharge\nIf you experience any of these signs, notify your doctor immediately.",
          "fetus_content_w7":
              "His limbs will grow further, and his elbows will start to form.\nHis toes will appear more distinct.\nHis ears and eyelids will continue to develop as well.\nThe umbilical cord – which will provide your fetus with nutrients and rid his wastes – will start to form.\nHis lungs and digestive system will continue to develop.\nIf you are carrying twins, you may experience the following:\n* More fatigue\n* More rapid weight gain\n* More fluid retention\nAt this stage, you may start to feel relief from some of the symptoms that you have been experiencing, especially morning sickness.",
          "fetus_content_w8":
              "During this week, your fetus’s head will take more of a round shape. His neck will develop and begin to grow. His eyes will become more visible due to the retina, and will become covered by the eyelids for protection. His brain will become clearly visible. His digestive system will continue to develop with the lengthening of the intestines and the formation of the anus.You fetus’s heart and circulatory system – which began to form during the fourth week – are already working quite well.  His bones will start to shape, joints will begin to appear in his elbows and fingers, and his tail will begin to disappear. \nThis week will mark the end of the embryonic stage, after which your fetus will officially become a fetus.",
          "fetus_content_w9":
              "Your fetus is now a fetus. He weighs around 2 grams, and measures around 2.3 cm in length. At the beginning of this week, your fetus’s head measures approximately half his length. From now on however, his torso and remaining body parts will experience more rapid growth as compared to the head. His eyes are far apart, his eyelids are fused, and his ears are depressed.  Red blood cells begin to form in his liver. \nSex organs will have formed by the end of this week: the penis if it is a boy, or the clitoris and the labia majora (the longitudinal skin folds) if it is a girl.",
          "fetus_content_w10":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 4 grams, and measures around 3.1 cm in length. \nHis nails will begin to appear during this week, and his face will start to develop its human features. The brain experiences very rapid growth, with 250,000 neurons forming every minute. Sex organs continue to develop. If your fetus is a boy, his testes will start to release testosterone (the male hormone). Tooth buds will begin to form. By the end of this week, his vital organs will have taken their shapes and started to function",
          "fetus_content_w11":
              "Your fetus weighs approximately 8 grams, and measures around 4.1 cm in length. \nThe iris will start to develop. The fingers and toes within the web-like hands and feet will separate completely, and the nails will become visible. At this stage, all the main body parts are formed, with the external ones well visible. All these body parts will continue to grow and to develop rapidly throughout pregnancy, especially until the 20th week. Sex organs continue to develop rapidly as well. In compensation, there will be an increase in the number of blood vessels in the placenta to provide sufficient nutrients to your growing fetus. ",
          "fetus_content_w12":
              "Your fetus weighs approximately 14 grams, and has reached around 5.4 cm in length. His developed muscles can now allow him to move. His heartbeats average 160 per minute, and are now audible using a Doppler. You can now notice his general facial features such as the tiny nose and the chin. Your fetus can now yawn and swallow. \nYou may start to experience less fatigue and morning sickness. You may also notice the lineanigra – a dark line running from your pubic area to your belly button.  \nBy this stage of pregnancy, the chances of miscarriage have dropped to less than 5%.",
          "fetus_content_w13":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 23 grams, and measures around 6.7 cm in length. His intestines will begin to transfer from within the umbilical cord to his abdominal cavity, and intestinal villi begin to appear. The pancreas is formed by this stage and will begin to secrete insulin. The placenta develops further by the end of the first trimester and begins to secrete hormones. \nYour fetus may start to suck his thumb. \nBy this time, your morning sickness will begin to disappear, and you will begin to feel more energized. If you still happen to be experiencing morning sickness, eat smaller and more frequent meals to avoid hunger that is suggested to trigger the nausea. \nElevated progesterone levels may slow your intestinal activity, causing hardening of the feces, and thus constipation. To manage or ease constipation: Drink 2 liters of water daily and eat more vegetables, fresh fruit, and dry fruit such as raisins and dried apricots.\nNow is the time when people around you might start to notice that you are pregnant, and now is the time when you are about to start enjoying your most beautiful pregnancy period.\nFYI: Fatty fish, walnuts, soybean, and seed oils are rich sources of omega-3 fatty acids which is necessary for the development of your fetus’s brain.",
          "fetus_content_w14":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 43 grams, and measures around 8.7 cm. \nYour fetus’s tiny kidneys have started to produce urine. Your fetus releases his urine into the amniotic fluid, which is recycled every three hours. To support this recycling process, it is important that you drink enough water and fluids. \nHair and eyebrows will start to grow, andlanugo – fine, soft, unpigmented downy hair – will begin to cover your fetus’s body for protection. The prostate will begin to develop in a boy, and the ovaries will descend from the abdomen into the pelvis in a girl. \nHormonal changes will produce further differences in your body that you may notice such as enlarged and darkened nipples. TheLinea nigra running from your pubis up to your belly button (or sometimes higher) will become more apparent.",
          "fetus_content_w15":
              "Your fetus weighs approximately 70 grams, and measures around 10.1 cm in length. His heart can now pump around 25 liters (6.6 gallons) of blood daily [at birth, his heart will be able to pump 300 liters (79.3 gallons) daily]. Follicles will begin to produce the pigment responsible for your fetus’s hair color. He will now be able to make a fist and bend his elbows, and reach his thumb to his mouth. His bones and muscles will continue to develop.\nYour heart will be pumping 20% more blood to nourish your fetus at this stage. Now might be the time to shop for maternity clothes, as you may not fit into what you have anymore.",
          "fetus_content_w16":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 80 grams, and measures around 11.6 cm in height. His ears will now relocate from the neck to the head, and he can now respond to stimuli on his cheek and suck his thumb. Your fetus is emptying his bladder every 30 to 45 minutes. By this week, his genitals are well noticeable, and your doctor can perform an ultrasound to determine whether you are having a boy or a girl. \nIt is mostly during this week when your fetus will be able to lift his head and you will begin to feel  him moving. He will begin to produce eye movements and facial expressions due to further development of facial muscles.",
          "fetus_content_w17":
              "Your fetus weighs approximately 100 grams, and measures around 12 cm in length. You may begin to feel him moving, and he may respond to loud sounds from the outer world. Fatty deposits will begin to set underneath his skin, while vernix caseosa – a cheesy waxy layer specialized to protect your fetus’s skin and keep him warm – begins to develop on his skin.\nThe larger volume of blood running throughout your body at this stage might produce more body changes that you may start to experience, such as increased sweating, nasal congestion, vaginal discharges, and larger breasts with visible veins. Consider switching to a bigger bra size that will fit your enlarged breasts more comfortably throughout the remainder of your pregnancy. \nIt is around this time of pregnancy when your gravity center will begin to shift. You may experience some loss of balance and some lower-back pain. To keep your balance and to protect your lower-back, avoid high-heel shoes, and maintain correct posture while standing and sitting.",
          "fetus_content_w18":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 200 grams, and measures around 14 cm in length. His bones have now grown stronger and harder, and his tiny fingers are starting to develop their prints. Thanks to the developing ear ossicles and nerve endings, your fetus’s responses to outer stimuli are now further developed. His eyes continue to develop, and the retina is now sensitive to light shined towards your belly. \nYour sexual appetite may start to improve at this point due to the elevated estrogen levels.  So be sure to get comfortable during lovemaking.  On the other hand, you might not find sleeping positions as comfortable during this period.",
          "fetus_content_w19":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 240 grams, and measures around 15.3 cm. Lanugo – the very fine, soft, unpigmented downy hair - that has begun to develop earlier, now covers you fetus’s entire body and will remain until near birth. Vernix caseosa – a cheesy waxy substance –also covers his skin for protection. Permanent teeth buds will form underneath the fetus teeth buds. \nYou may be experiencing fluctuations in your sex drive. Keep in mind that sex usually creates no harm as long as you are having a healthy pregnancy.",
          "fetus_content_w20":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 300 grams, and measures around 16.4 cm in length. This fast growing fetus will create more pressure on your internal organs such as your lungs, your stomach, your kidneys, and your bladder. As a result from the upward and outward pressure on your bladder, your belly button may protrude and may remain like that until your fetus drops to your pelvic area in a process called lightening.",
          "fetus_content_w21":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 350 grams, and measures around 26 cm in length. He is still able to freely move in the amniotic fluid. His heartbeats are now stronger, and his intestines are more developed and able to absorb the little sugar quantities swallowed with the amniotic fluid. Although so far, the liver and the spleen have been responsible for red blood cell production (and will carry on this function until birth) it is now when the bone marrow will begin to participate in this process. \nYou may have an improved appetite due to the 500 calorie increase in your daily requirement during your2ndtrimester. The increase in your body size may now be obvious, and your waistline may no longer be noticeable. \nExercise is the ideal way to stay fit, and can also ease some complications such as lower-back pain and varicose veins, and can help avoid excessive weight gain. However, strenuous exercise must be avoided. \nThis is the perfect time for you and your husband to start talking to your fetus, as he will recognize mommy and daddy’s voices after birth.",
          "fetus_content_w22":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 425 grams, and measures around 27 cm in height. His eyebrows and eyelids have now taken their shapes.  His senses have developed, and taste buds will begin to form on his tongue. His brain and nerve endings are developing further as well. The reproductive system is continuing to develop. \nIf you have a boy, the testicles will begin to descend. If you have a girl, the vagina will have fully developed by now. The skin continues to develop as well, with vernix caseosa still protecting it from the amniotic fluid. A layer of hair now covers his head to regulate his temperature. His legs have now become more proportionate in length to his body. Your fetus is able to perceive light even with his eyes closed. If you shine a light on your belly, you will feel him move toward it. \nYour breasts are still enlarging and still sore and tingling. The pressure from your uterus on your lower-back is painful. Avoid wearing high-heel shoes, and avoid standing or sitting for long periods. \nAt this stage, you may begin to experience irregular and non-painful contractions called Braxton-Hicks contractions. However, if these contractions become painful, or if they exceed four per hour, inform your doctor immediately, as this may be a sign of early labor.",
          "fetus_content_w23":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 500 grams, and measures around 29 cm in length. His body is becoming more and more proportionate. \nYour fetus is moving his fingers, toes, and arms regularly, and you can definitely feel his kicks by now. The ossicles in the middle ear are beginning to harden and the pigments responsible for his skin color are being released during this week.\nAlthough you now feel that you have restored some of your energy, the hormonal changes are causing a few disturbances such as eye dryness.If you are experiencing difficulties with your contact lenses, consult your ophthalmologist. Other disturbances you may experience include heartburn and indigestion.  Avoid high fat foods and fatty meals in this case.  \nYou may be lacking sleep due to anxiety, frequent toilet visits at night, heartburn, or leg and foot cramps. Keep in mind that plenty of rest is essential for your health and for your fetus’s health as well. A warm bath or a warm cup of milk can prepare your body better for sleep. Sleep on your side, rather than on your back or on your belly, to allow adequate blood flow to the placenta. If this position is uncomfortable, place a pillow between your knees to minimize the pressure on your side while asleep.",
          "fetus_content_w24":
              "Your fetus weighs approximately 600 grams, and measures around 30 cm. Is your fetus kicking when you are surrounded by loud noises?  That is because his hearing is becoming more and more acute. Around this time of pregnancy, his lungs will start to produce surfactant, a substance in the alveoli that protects them from collapsing, thus keeping the lungs expanded to facilitate breathing after the fetus is born. Your fetus will be alternating between sleep and wake-up periods, and you may notice him becoming more active when you choose to rest and relax, so get ready for what will come next!\nYou should expect your doctor to order a glucose screening testanytime between 24 and 28 weeks of pregnancy to check for gestational diabetes (pregnancy diabetes). When diagnosed, gestational diabetes can put the fetus at risk for low blood glucose levels and high-birth weight, and the mother at risk for delivery by c-section due to the large fetus size.  This app is designed to remind you when your test is due.\nFYI: Remember to add anti-oxidant rich foods to your diet, such as fresh vegetable and fruit juices (tomato juice, grape juice, and pomegranate juice).",
          "fetus_content_w25":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 700 grams, and measuresaround 35 cm in length. His developed little hands can now make a fist and perceive tangible matters around him such as his skin and umbilical cord. You are continuing to notice when he is active and when he is quiet, especially at night. His brain is very close to attaining the shape of a newborn’s. He has a fully developed sense of hearing that allows him to recognize your voice. The vertebral column – that will compose of 33 vertebrae, 150 joints, and 1000 ligaments, will begin to form. Blood vessels in his lungs will begin to form, and his nostril will open up. \nIndigestion, heartburn, shortness of breath, and swelling of the hands and of the feet are all unpleasant complications you may be experiencing from pregnancy. Seventy percent of pregnant women experience some skin discoloration of the face due to the elevated estrogen levels. Because exposure to sun in such cases can produce a darker skin color, sun-block creams are recommended. \nBe sure to make time for regular exercise and relaxation techniques to preserve your strength and energy for labor. Be aware of early labor signs.\nEnsure that everything you eat is well cooked. Focus on steamed and roasted foods, and foods sautéed with no added fats, such as baked fish. Try to eat small and frequent meals throughout the day. Avoid fatty and spicy foods.",
          "fetus_content_w26":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 760 grams and measures around 35 cm. His eyes that have been closed so far to allow the retina to develop can start to blink around this week. Eye color is highly dependent on race. Some babies are born with dark eyes, while others are born with light or mixed-color eyes. In some babies, eye color can change within the first six months of life. Hair and eyelashes are still continuing to grow.  Although your fetus still has no air to breathe at this point, he is breathing the amniotic fluid around him, a process offering him good training to prepare him for breathing after birth.\nInclude fiber-rich foods in your diet, such as whole-grain bread and cereal, lentils, and brown rice. These can help to ease you from constipation, and are good sources of B-vitamins.",
          "fetus_content_w27":
              "Your fetus now weighs approximately 870 grams and measures around 36 cm. He is continuing to grow, his brain is becoming more efficient, and his lungs are continuing to develop. He is opening and closing his eyes according to a more regular sleep cycle that he is developing. You may start to experience some fluid retention around this time of pregnancy, and your shoes may not fit anymore. As a precaution, remove any rings off your fingers. If you are experiencing back pain, place a pillow behind your back while seated. \nIf you are a vegetarian, be sure to include enough protein-rich plant foods in your diet to ensure adequate amino acid intake. Consult a dietitian to learn more about essential amino acid content in plant foods and making the choices right for you. Some popular protein-rich plant foods are lentils, beans, chickpeas, rice, wheat, nuts, and seeds.",
          "fetus_content_w28":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 1005 grams, and measures around 37.5 cm. His eyes and eyelashes are completely developed. If you shine a light towards your belly, your fetus will open his eyes and turn his head towards it!\nYour doctor should soon find out your fetus’s position in your womb: vertex (head up), breech (head down), or transverse (across) position. This gives an approximate judgment about whether you will give birth vaginally or by a c-section. Do not panic if your fetus is in a breech position now. He still has plenty of time ahead to flip to a vertex position, which happens commonly. \nYour fetus is creating pressure on your bladder, urging you to visit the bathroom more often. Do not let this stop you from drinking more water. If your legs are feeling tired or heavy, raise them up for 10 or 15 minutes. Around this time, your fetus’s kicks may begin to wake you up at night.",
          "fetus_content_w29":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 1.2 kg, and measures around 38.6 cm. His head is now in better proportion with his body. Fat continues to deposit underneath his skin, and his brain can now control the primitive breathing in him. His eyes can now move and respond to light and dark.  His movements are becoming more efficient. However, if you noticed a decrease you must start counting them (you can use the KickTrackerprovided by this app). Notify your doctor if the movements are less than 10 distinct movements in two hours. \nYou may become uncomfortable with certain sensations or complications during the 3rdtrimester such as itching, shortness of breath, hemorrhoids, leg cramps, heartburn, or indigestion. Although disturbing, they luckily disappear right after delivery. The fundus (the top part of your uterus) is now lying around halfway between your bellybutton and your ribs, and is starting to protrude forward. If you have a boy, his testicles will lie close to kidneys. If you have a girl, her clitoris will be partially covered by the small developing labia that will soon grow to cover it entirely by the time she is born. \nYour fetus’s nutritional requirements will be at their highest during the 3rdtrimester. His brain is developing further, and his bones are growing stronger. Thus, you will need to ensure adequate protein, vitamin C, folic acid, iron, and calcium intake to meet these requirements. Anemia is not uncommon during pregnancy, which is why your doctor will order the appropriate tests to check your blood iron levels.",
          "fetus_content_w30":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 1.4 kg, and measures around 40 cm. He can blink perfectly, and his bones are mature enough to produce red blood cells. He is continuing to gain weight. Lanugo may start falling off his body, with the exception of his back and shoulders in some cases. \nConstipation – induced by hormonal changes – is a common pregnancy complication. Regular exercise and a high-fiber diet with increased fluid intake can help ease the condition by maintaining intestinal movement.  High-fiber foods include vegetables, legumes, and whole grains. \nMake sure your food is well cooked, and your vegetables are thoroughly washed to protect your fetus from harmful bugs.",
          "fetus_content_w31":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 1.5 kg, and measures around 41cm. His brain and lungs will enter a rapid developmental stage. If it is a boy, the testicles will begin to descend from the abdominal cavity to the scrotum. Your fetus requires calcium now more than any time before to nourish his growing and hardening bones. Seek advice from your healthcare professional to ensure adequate intake of calcium, protein, iron, and amino acids through your diet. \nThe placenta will provide your fetus with all his nutritional requirements. He will release around ½ liter of urine per day in the surrounding amniotic fluid. Your fetus swallows some of this fluid that is recycled multiple times per day. \nHydramnios (too much amniotic fluid in the amniotic sac) is a condition caused multiple factors, such as the fetus’s inability to properly swallow the fluid. Be aware of warning signs and symptoms such as shortness of breath, cramps, or bloating or swelling in your belly. \nOligoamnios (little amniotic fluid in the sac) can be caused by a urinary blockage or a kidney problem preventing the fetus from urinating. Oligoamnios may have no signs beside vaginal discharges and a small belly size compared to gestational age. \nIf hydramnios or oligoamnios are suspected, your doctor will conduct an ultrasound test to measure the amniotic fluid.\nAround this time, your milk secreting glands may begin to produce colostrum- a thick yellow liquid produced by your breasts usually during the first few days following birth, with increased production occurring around the third or the fourth day. Colostrum is easily digested in the fetus’s immature digestive tract, and is a rich source of antibodies and essential nutrients. Remarkable milk production usually starts around the third or the fourth day after birth.",
          "fetus_content_w32":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 1.8 kg, and measures around 42 cm. All five senses are now developed. He now has grown fingernails, toenails, and eyelashes, and more hair on his head. More of the lanugo that covered his body during the first trimester is shedding off. \nYour enlarged uterus can give you heartburn, constipation, indigestion, and shortness of breath. Drinking large amounts of fluids and eating smaller and more frequent meals high in fiber can help you manage these complications.",
          "fetus_content_w33":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 2 kg, and has reached around 43 cm in length. His lungs are almost mature, and he will be gaining weight remarkably during the remaining weeks in your womb. The fat that will continue to deposit underneath his skin until birth will begin to give him a lighter pink color. About now, your fetus settles into his final position before birth: vertex or breech.\nThe millions of neurons in his brain are allowing your fetus to perceive the surrounding environment. He can listen and feel. His pupils can constrict and dilate in response to light, giving him blurred vision.\nIf this is your first pregnancy, there is a 50% chance that your fetus moves his head toward your pelvis around this week, which will create pressure on your cervix. If this is your second pregnancy, this may not happen until around one week before labor, or even right at its onset.",
          "fetus_content_w34":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 2.25 kg, and measures around 45 cm in length. His nails have reached the tip of his fingers. Although his immune system is developed enough to fight mild infections, it is still not ready for rougher infections. His tiny feet are continuing to grow as his toes and heels are developing. \nCalcium is an essential nutrient in your diet throughout your pregnancy. Your fetus’s bones are depending on your calcium stores for growth and strength. A calcium deficiency can thus weaken your bones and teeth. \nBy the end of this week, the risk for preterm labor is no longer present. Ninety nine percent of babies born in the 35th week can normally survive without suffering any complications. At this time, the central nervous system is continuing to develop, and the lungs are very close to reaching their maturity. \nTry to relax and get enough sleep. Fatigue is commonly experienced from sleep deficiency, pain, weight gain, and nervousness about the approaching due date.",
          "fetus_content_w35":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 2.4 Kg, and measures around 46 cm in length. More fat is being deposited underneath his skin, especially in his arms and legs. He is now going through a growth spurt, during which his weight will increase by 250 to 350 grams per week. His growing size will begin to crowd your womb, causing either weaker or stronger movements. The number of movements, however, should remain the same. Your fetus’s liver is now fully developed and will begin to process his waste products. \nThis rapid fetus growth and crowding of the womb can give mommy shortness of breath, indigestion, and heartburn. Stay physically active! There might also be less amniotic fluid now in the crowded womb. Thus, make sure you drink enough water and fluids, even if it is making you visit the bathroom more often. \nYou may experience a boost in your sex drive. Keep exercising, and include food items to your diet that enhance your sexual desires, such as bananas and raisins. \nStarting from this week, you need to schedule weekly appointments with your healthcare provider.",
          "fetus_content_w36":
              "Your fetus weighs around 2.6 kg and measures around 47 cm.\nYour fetus no longer has enough room to kick and play anymore.\nPreparing for birth, he is now moving downward towards your pelvis.\nYour fetus is now ready for the outside world!\nAs he moves down towards your pelvis, you may begin to breathe better.\nThe decreased pressure on your stomach and intestines will relieve you from heartburn, allowing your appetite to improve.\nAt this point, you should schedule weekly visits to your healthcare provider to measure cervical dilation and effacing (thinning out).\nWith around one month left until your fetus arrives, here are a few helpful reminders:\n* Consider a visit to the hospital where you are planning to give birth, and check out the delivery room.\n* Make sure all the necessary arrangements are done in your home to welcome the new fetus, and be sure to add all the final touches and not to miss out any of the items on your shopping list.\n* Keep in mind that your fetus may be born any minute! So have your hospital suitcase packed and ready.",
          "fetus_content_w37":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 2.95 kg, and measures around 48.5 cm. In many babies, hair is covering the entire scalp at this time. Your fetus can breathe and can make a strong fist. He can also respond to the light that you shine on your belly. You may have some vaginal discharges, and increased cervical mucus. \nAlthough your fetus is fully developed by this week, he is still continuing to grow. Fat is still continuing to deposit under his skin by around 14 grams every day (a little more in boys than in girls). Your fetus is now settled in his final position for birth. \nThe mucus plug – a thick greenish mucus substance sometimes tinged with blood, which protects your uterus from microbes and infections – may discharge any time from a few hours to a few weeks prior to labor. However, there is a chance that it may dislodge around this week. \nWith antibodies from mommy, fetus’s immune system is becoming stronger and more protective against diseases. \nDietary zinc is essential for enhancing the immune system, maintaining the senses of smell and taste, and promoting wound healing during pregnancy. Legumes such as chickpeas and lentils, wheat grains, meat, and tuna fish are good sources of zinc.",
          "fetus_content_w38":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 3.1 kg, and measures around 50 cm. He is gaining weight regularly by the day. His intestines are beginning to collect meconium, fetus’s first stool! Meconium is a dark green fecal matter composed from a mix of intestinal cells, hair, and dead skin cells that fetus has swallowed and stored in his intestines. In a boy, testicles have descended to the scrotum by now, whereas the labia in a girl are fully developed. \nYou may begin to experience false contractions in your lower belly and pelvic area. True labor is felt in the upper area of the uterus, and spreads throughout the belly and the lower back. See the difference between True and False contractions in this App.\nThe pressure from your fetus is making you visit the bathroom more often.",
          "fetus_content_w39":
              "Your fetus now weighs around 3.2 kg, and measures around 51 cm. His body parts and organs are now fully developed and mature. The placenta has now reached its functional peak in nourishing your fetus. His lungs are almost fully functioning. His nails have grown beyond his fingertips, and his skin is now as soft as it can be. \nYour fetus is beginning to settle in your womb. There is now less pressure on your lungs, and you are breathing much better. On the other hand, there is more pressure created on your bladder now than ever, making you rush to the bathroom so often. \nYour water can break any minute! It is experienced differently from one woman to another. While some may feel a large flood, others may feel little dripping and wetting continuously. If this happens, or if you begin to experience contractions, notify your healthcare provider immediately. \nYour fetus is now finding it more difficult to move and kick. The umbilical cord – which carries to him oxygen and nutrients – measures around 50 cm, and has a diameter of around 1.3 cm. It may wrap around your now large fetus or forms knots. Most of the vernix caseosa on your fetus’s skin will have disappeared by now. \nYour baby is ready to come out!",
          "fetus_content_w40":
              "By birth, your baby can weigh anywhere between 3.2 and 4 kg, and can measure from 48 to 56 cm.\nHe has now attained his largest size within your womb, and has very little free space around him.\nAlmost there! You can give birth any minute!\nHowever, if it does not happen now, it is not too late yet.\nYou still have two more weeks ahead before you are considered post-term, especially if this is your first pregnancy.\nYou may begin to experience pre-labor pain.\nJust relax, and enjoy every moment.\nYour baby is just as excited as you are!\nYou may crave desserts at this time.\nDark chocolate (rich in anti-oxidants) is a good choice to satisfy that sweet tooth.\nFoods containing the amino acid tryptophan such as milk and dairy products are known to trigger sleep, and would be good choices to help you relax.\nIn labor, the mucus plug will be expelled, and you will notice bleeding.\nContractions will become sharper, and the amniotic fluid will start to leak once the amniotic sac breaks.\nThere are three stages of labor:\n* The first stage: during which your cervix dilates and effaces due to regular uterine contractions.\n* The second stage: during which your baby passes through the birth canal.\n* The third stage: this is the final stage, during which the placenta is expelled.\nThe shape of your baby’s head may look different.\nNothing to worry about, because this will not last long.\nThis is noticed in some newborns, as the skull bones – not yet fused – overlap a little to facilitate passage through the tight birth canal.\nWhen born, babies are usually covered with a greasy layer and with blood.\nYou may notice some rashes or dry spots on his soft skin. This is normal as well.\nThe genitals may be somewhat enlarged (the scrotum in a boy or the labia in the girl), but only temporarily.\nThis is due to the elevated hormone levels the baby was exposed to inside your body.\nThis hormone accumulation can also cause some milk to leak from the nipples (whether in a boy or in a girl), but this will disappear as well within a few days.\nAt this point, you are experiencing one of the most precious moments in your life, filled with emotions and feelings.\nGraviLog team would like to congratulate you and your family on your new baby, wishing you much happiness and prosperity ahead!\nWe hope that this App has been educative and helpful in guiding you through a safe and healthy pregnancy.\nCongratulations!",
          "the_dangers_of_malnutrition": "The Dangers of Malnutrition",
          "the_dangers_of_malnutrition_description":
              "It is very important that women should be prepared before or during pregnancy in terms of attention to good and balanced nutrition. This can be achieved by having a balanced and varied diet and dealing with nutritional supplements by consulting their doctor. The balanced and varied diet includes vegetables, fruits, animal products like meat, milk and dairy products, and carbohydrates such as fats and oils. So, having this will allow women to be well-prepared during pregnancy, childbirth, and breastfeeding without any problems related to the lack of various nutrients.\n\nPregnancy nutrition is essential to women's and fetus health, as unbalanced or insufficient nutrition increases the following potential risks:\n1- Suffering from different inflammations.\n2- Anemia.\n3- Feeling of drowsiness, apathy, lethargy, and lack of productivity.\n4- The death of the fetus or the baby later.\n5- Delays in fetal growth, low birth weight, or premature birth.\n6- Birth defects in the fetus.\n7- Delays in growth and development of the baby later.\n8- Increased medical complications for pregnant women and the risk of death.",
          "additional_nutritional_needs": "Additional Nutritional Needs:",
          "additional_nutritional_needs_description":
              "The pregnant woman's body needs an extra amount of energy, especially in the second trimester (240 kilocalories or one snack) and the third trimester (452 kilocalories or two snacks) of pregnancy. In case the pregnant woman doesn't consume extra food, the fetus will take his needs from the mother, leaving her with a lack of nutrients, which can create nutritional problems and lead to fatigue and weakness. Therefore, a pregnant woman should get extra energy by maintaining a balanced and varied diet.\n\nIn the second trimester, a snack for a pregnant woman means an extra meal such as a glass of milk, fruits, and a small sandwich. In the third trimester, she needs to consume two small meals or one medium meal to meet the additional energy demands of pregnancy.\n\nThe daily protein requirement for a pregnant woman is 9 grams of protein, which is available in one cup of milk, one cup of legumes, one serving of cheese, meat, etc. A breastfeeding woman requires 25 grams of additional protein on top of her pre-pregnancy daily needs.\n\nSince the daily requirements for folic acid and iron during pregnancy cannot typically be met through diet alone, supplementation with folic acid and iron is recommended under the guidance of a physician.",
          "essential_nutrients": "Essential Nutrients",
          "essential_nutrients_description":
              "Please note that it is preferable to take them from the natural sources mentioned below and not to take any dietary supplements except after consulting your doctor and conducting the necessary tests. Protein: • Protein is essential for your fetus’s development, especially during the second and third trimesters. • Good protein sources include meat, chicken, eggs, and legumes such as beans, green peas, dairy products, and peanut butter. • Your daily requirement of protein is 67 grams. Iron: • Iron is essential for hemoglobin formation, which is responsible for transporting and delivering oxygen to your fetus. The need for iron increases during pregnancy due to the increase in your fluid volume and the increasing demand for this mineral in your growing fetus. • Inadequate iron intake in your diet can lead to fatigue, microbial infections, pre-term labor, and low birth weight. • Good sources of iron include red meat, chicken, fish, legumes, and dark leafy vegetables such as spinach, hibiscus, cabbage, rocca, and jew's mallow. It is also found in grains, dried fruits, and nuts. • Iron from animal sources is easily absorbed in the intestines, which is not the case with plant foods. To optimize iron absorption from plant foods, add vitamin C-rich sources to the same meal, such as lemon juice, orange juice, strawberry juice, guava juice, green peppers, and tomatoes. • The intake of iron and folic acid supplements is necessary starting at the fourth month of pregnancy until three months after birth. These supplements are usually provided at the Ministry of Health clinics or by women's healthcare providers. • Your daily requirement of iron is 27 mg. Folate: • Folate (vitamin B9) is necessary for the development of the spinal cord in your fetus. • Insufficient intake during pregnancy may lead to neurological defects in the brain or spinal cord, known as Spina bifida. It can also lead to pre-term labor or low birth weight. • Rich sources of folate include citrus fruits like oranges and lemons, green leafy vegetables such as spinach, rocca, lettuce, and jew’s mallow, beans, green peas, walnuts, red meats, poultry, and fish. Folate is available in supplements as folic acid, the synthetic form. To ensure sufficient intake, supplements are recommended three months prior to pregnancy until the end of the third month of pregnancy (These supplements are usually provided at the Ministry of Health maternity clinics for free). Taking enough quantity prevents fetal malformations. • You will need 600 mcg of folate daily starting three months before your pregnancy and throughout it. Calcium: • Calcium is essential for the development of bones and teeth formation; it also aids in improving your blood circulation and is necessary for your muscles and nerves. • Good sources of calcium include dairy products, dark-colored vegetables, and fish, especially canned fish. • Your daily requirement of calcium is 1000 mg. If you are younger than 20 and pregnant, your daily requirement increases to 1300 mg. Vitamin D: • Vitamin D is essential in promoting bone and teeth development in your fetus. • Good sources include fatty fish like tuna and salmon, milk, and vitamin D fortified orange juices. • Your daily requirement of vitamin D is 600 IU.\n",
          "nutritional_recommendations": "Nutritional Recommendations ",
          "nutritional_recommendations_description":
              "1. Eat plenty of animal source foods, fresh vegetables and fruits, and legumes such as lentils, beans, chickpeas, and fava beans. 2. Ensure variety in your diet. Include a variety of foods from each food group: a variety of legumes, vegetables, fruits, dairy products, eggs, meats, and fats. 3. Consume fortified foods such as enriched breads and iodised salt. Keep in mind that proper iodine intake is essential during pregnancy as it helps greatly in protecting your fetus from mental retardation. 4. To facilitate iron absorption, consume iron-rich foods, such as red meats, liver (once a week), chicken, seafood, lentils, beans, green beans, and spinach along with vitamin C-rich foods such as citrus fruits, tomatoes, green peppers, and guava. 5. Consume plenty of fiber-rich foods such as fruits, green peppers, lettuce, rocca, whole legumes, bran, and whole wheat bread (bran and whole wheat bread contain phytates, substances that interfere with iron absorption. Thus, phytate-rich foods must be consumed in moderation). 6. Drink tea and coffee in moderation. These drinks are sources of tannins, substances that interfere with iron absorption. Avoid alcoholic drinks, sodas, and energy drinks. Consume a variety of herbs such as chamomile, aniseed, tamarind, and carob. 7. Do not drink milk or have dairy products with meals or within two hours following a meal, as they are high in calcium which interferes with iron absorption. Be sure, however, to include milk and dairy products in your daily diet. 8. Consume adequate amounts of vitamin A-rich foods such as liver (once weekly), red meats, eggs, carrots, and pumpkin. 9. Ensure proper cleanliness of dishes and equipment used in food preparation. 10. Do not eat onions and garlic in large amounts during breastfeeding, as they may alter the taste of your breastmilk. 11. Do not take any folk advice regarding your nutrition without consulting with your physician, nurse, dietitian, or health educator. 12. Although you are allowed to consume a variety of seafood twice weekly such as shrimp, salmon, canned tuna, tilapia, catfish, and cod; avoid raw and undercooked fish such as oysters and smoked fish. 13. Avoid undercooked meats, poultry, and eggs. 14. Avoid unpasteurised foods such as unpasteurised milk, unpasteurised cheeses like blue cheese and those processed from unpasteurised milk; and unpasteurised juices, as these foods may be contaminated with microbes. 15. Avoid foods high in sugar, saturated fats (butter, ghee, and grease), and trans fats such as hydrogenated fats and margarine. Avoid sodas, energy drinks, fast foods, and processed foods. 16. Make yourself familiar with the ingredients and nutritional value of different food items by reading food labels regularly. 17. Stay physically active. Talk to your physician about physical activities that are right for you. 18. Get some rest. Minimize strenuous activities and working hours to support your body’s metabolism and deliver energy and nutrients to your fetus. 19. Read handouts regarding nutrition during pregnancy and breastfeeding approved by the Ministry of Health or by your physician.\n",
          "medications_beverages": "Medications and Beverages",
          "medications_beverages_description":
              "1. Introduction: 2. From the very first day, your embryo embarks on the most critical developmental journey of its life, where the fundamental formation of its organs, parts, systems, and senses takes place. During this period, its growth depends on you, through the nourishment and oxygen provided by your bloodstream that reaches it via the placenta's selective function. However, some harmful substances manage to penetrate the placenta, causing harm to the embryo and negatively impacting its growth, organ development, and function, sometimes even posing a threat to its life. 3. Medications are among the substances that pregnant women must be cautious about. While some medications may be safe and necessary to treat an illness or alleviate symptoms, it is crucial for pregnant women to consult their doctors before taking any medication (or before discontinuing any as well). While there are other medications that pregnant women are advised to avoid due to the potential for negative effects, there is a list of medications that doctors and scientists unanimously agree are dangerous, as they have resulted in birth defects, organ malformations, or functional disabilities in the fetus. This list is summarized below. 4. In addition, we will provide an explanation of vaccines, herbal remedies, nutritional supplements, and prohibited beverages.\n",
          "prohibited_drinking": "Prohibited Drinking",
          "prohibited_drinking_description":
              "* Alcohol:  Can cause severe abnormalities in the head and in the face, such as in fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS). It can also cause mental retardation and other defects in the central nervous system. * Caffeine: Over-consumption can lead to a miscarriage. Limit your caffeine consumption to less than 200 mg of caffeine per day, the equivalent of two cups of instant coffee, or one cup of filtered coffee. * Cigarette smoking: smoking can lead to cleft palate, early labor, and low-birth weight.\n",
          "all_vaccines": "All Vaccines",
          "all_vaccines_description":
              "It is strongly recommended that you consult your doctor before taking any type of vaccine. This includes both routine vaccines and new or previously unavailable vaccines.\nThe reason for this is that vaccines contain different ingredients and work in different ways, and there can be potential effects on pregnancy or the fetus. There are vaccines that are safe to use during pregnancy, while others may have concerns. Therefore, pregnant women should consult their doctors to assess the potential benefits and risks of receiving the vaccine and provide appropriate guidance based on their specific health status and individual pregnancy situation.\nIn general, doctors recommend that vaccines be given during pregnancy only when they are considered effective and safe, after careful medical evaluation.\n",
          "herbal_remedies_nutritional_supplements":
              "Herbal Remedies and Nutritional Supplements",
          "herbal_remedies_nutritional_supplements_description":
              "No one knows for sure whether certain products such as herbs, minerals, amino acids, and dietary supplements are safe for pregnant women. Therefore, it is not recommended to take any of them before consulting your doctor. With the exception of what we know about certain vitamins, not much is known about the effects of using dietary supplements for pregnant women. However, safety dictates that a pregnant woman should talk to her doctor before using any herbal product or dietary supplement. Some herbs may be helpful in relieving common pregnancy symptoms, but it is important to consult your doctor before using any of them as some may affect pregnancy or fetal health. Possible Effects: Some herbs may interact with prescribed medications or cause unwanted side effects. Common and Used Herbs: * Ginger: Used to relieve nausea and vomiting and is generally safe in small amounts, but a doctor should be consulted if there are concerns about bleeding. * Chamomile: Helps with relaxation and sleep and is safe in small amounts but should be used with caution as it may cause drowsiness. * Peppermint: Used to relieve gas and indigestion and is safe in small amounts, but may cause heartburn. * Oats: Helps relieve stress and anxiety and is generally safe. Herbs to Avoid: * Black cohosh: May cause uterine contractions. * Licorice: May raise blood pressure and affect hormone levels. * Rosemary: May cause uterine contractions and affect blood circulation. Nutritional Supplements: Nutritional supplements play an important role in supporting the health of the pregnant woman and the development of the fetus. It is important to choose supplements carefully and consult with your doctor before starting any of them. Essential Supplements: * Folic acid: Essential to prevent neural tube defects in the fetus. Recommended intake is 400-800 micrograms daily. * Iron: Important to prevent anemia and support fetal growth. Recommended daily intake is 27-30 milligrams. * Calcium: Supports bone and teeth health for both mother and baby. Recommended daily intake is around 1000 milligrams. * Vitamin D: Enhances calcium absorption and supports immune system health. Recommended daily intake is 600 IU. * Omega-3 (DHA): Essential for brain and eye development in the fetus. Recommended daily intake is around 200-300 milligrams. Supplements to Avoid: * Vitamin A: High doses can be toxic and cause birth defects. * Vitamin E: High doses may increase the risk of bleeding. General Tips: * Consult your doctor: Always before starting any type of herbal remedy or dietary supplement. * Recommended dosages: Do not exceed the recommended dosages to avoid potential side effects. * Natural products: Choose high-quality products that are certified by reputable health organizations. Balanced diet: Focus on consuming a balanced and varied diet to obtain essential vitamins and minerals naturally.\n",
          "medications_avoid_pregnancy_breastfeeding":
              "Medications to Avoid During Pregnancy and breastfeeding",
          "medications_avoid_pregnancy_breastfeeding_description":
              "• Thalidomide\\n• Brand names: Thalidomid, Talider, Talidex, and Immunoprin.\\n• Indications: treatment of leprosy, tuberculosis and multiple myeloma.\\n• Teratogenic effects: may cause shortening of the limbs in the fetus, and malformations of the eyes, external ears, digestive and urinary tracts, reproductive system; facial paralysis, and congenital heart defects. Increases the chances of miscarriage. Consult your physician immediately if you get pregnant while taking this medication, or if you have been prescribed this medication while breastfeeding.\\n• Retinoids\\n• Vitamin A derivatives.\\n• Topical Tretinoin\\n• Brand names: Ret-Avit, Rootan, Aberela, Airol, A-Ret, Atralin, Avita, Retacnyl, Refissa, Renova, Retin-A, Retino-A, ReTrieve, or Stieva-A.\\n• Usually in the form of topical ointments, used in the treatment of acne.\\n• Causes miscarriage in pregnant women.\\n• Causes fetal malformations: in the nervous and musculoskeletal systems, external ears, eyes, glands, and blood vessels; dysmorphia and cleft palate, and thyroid hormone deficiency.\\n• Women planning on getting pregnant are advised to discontinue tretinoin for at least one month, due to the body’s high capacity of storing the medication.\\n• Consult your physician should there be an urgent need of taking the medication during pregnancy.\\n• Breastfeeding women must discontinue breastfeeding should there be a need to take this medication due to the potential of dangerous side effects in infants.\\n• Isotretinoin\\n• Brand names: Roacutane, Curatane, Accutane, Claravis, Sotret, Amnesteem.\\n• Usually in the form of oral pills.\\n• Indications: treatment of Acne\\n• Teratogenic effects: Highly teratogenic, increasing the risk of hydrocephalus (water in the brain), malformations of the heart, eyes, and ears; and cleft palate.\\n• Because they can be easily stored in the body, isotretinoin and tretinoin must be discontinued, at least six months and one month, respectively, before conception.\\n• Women of child bearing age must be on two forms of contraception while taking Isotretinoin.\\n• If you or your partner are on Isotretinoin and are planning on becoming pregnant, consult your doctor about discontinuing the medication.\\n• Not much is known about the secretion of this medication in breastmilk. Therefore, the company recommends the discontinuation of breastfeeding before starting this medication due to the potential of dangerous side effects in breastfed infants.\\n• Acitretin\\n• Brand names: Soriatane, Neotigason\\n• Available in the form of pills.\\n• Used in treatment of psoriasis.\\n• Causes fetal malformations of the brain, ears, heart, bones, hips, ankles, vertebrae, skull, forearms, and palate.\\n• Women using this medication are advised to wait 3 years before getting pregnant due to the body’s high capacity of storing it. The husband as well is advised to discontinue the medication when planning on getting pregnant. Medical advice is recommended in this case.\\n• This medication must not be taken while breastfeeding because it is secreted in breastmilk.\\n• Tazarotene\\n• Brand names: Tazorac, Avage, Zorac, and Fabior.\\n• Available in the form of cream and topical gel.\\n• Used in the treatment of psoriasis and acne.\\n• Causes malformations in animal fetuses: low fetal weight, low bone density, spina bifida, hydrocephalus, and heart defects.\\n• Breastfeeding women must consult a physician should they need to take this medication.\\n• A woman planning on a pregnancy is advised to discontinue the medication at least one month before due to the body’s high capacity of storing it.\\n• Methotrexate\\n• Brand names: Abitrexate, Rheumatrex\\n• Available as pills, intravascular injections, and intramuscular injections.\\n• Indications: used for abortion and treatment of cancer, psoriasis, and rheumatoid arthritis.\\n• Causes fetal malformations: in the extremities, neurological malformations such as spina bifida, mental retardation; tetralogy of Fallot, lung and heart malformations, mental retardation, and sudden infant death syndrome.\\n• Causes miscarriages in pregnant women.\\n• Must not be used by pregnant women with psoriases or arthritis.\\n• For cancer treatment, a physician must be consulted prior to taking this medication.\\n• This medication is contraindicated for breastfeeding mothers.\\n• A woman planning on getting pregnant is advised to discontinue the medication for at least one month due to the body’s high capacity of storing it.\\n• The husband as well must discontinue the medication for three months when planning a pregnancy. We recommend seeking medical advice in this case.\\n• Anticonvulsant medications\\n• Carbamazapine\\n• Brand names: Equetro, Carbatrol Tegretol, Teril\\n• Causes fetal malformations: spinal cord defects such as spina bifida and growth disorders; birth defects such as cranial nerve defects; heart, blood vessel, and brain defects.\\n• Available in the form of pills.\\n• Consult your physician should you have an urgent need to take this medication during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Valproic Acid\\n• Brand names: Divalproex, Depakote, Depakote ER, Depacon, Stavzor, Duvalep, Depalept, Depakene.\\n• Available in the form of pills and syrup.\\n• Used in treatment of epilepsy and in the prevention of migraines.\\n• Causes fetal malformations: malformations in the nervous system, heart, bones; face, urinary tract, reproductive system, and extremities; spina bifida, and neural tube defects.\\n• Consult your physician should you have an urgent need to take this medication during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Warfarin\\n• Brand names: Coumadin, Jantoven, Marevan, and Uniwarfin.\\n• Available in the form of pills.\\n• Indications: Anticoagulant.\\n• Teratogenic effects: Neurological defects, facial, heart, and bone malformations; and mental retardation.\\n• Consult your physician should you have an urgent need to take this medication while breastfeeding.\\n• Hormones\\n• Androgens\\n• Male hormones\\n• Danazole: Brand name of a synthetic male hormone used to treat endometriosis.\\n• Teratogenic effects: Masculinization of the female fetus.\\n• If you conceive while taking this medication, you must discontinue it immediately and consult your doctor.\\n• Contraindicated during breastfeeding.\\n• Diethylstillbestrol (DES)\\n• Indications: A synthetic estrogen that was used between the 1940’s and the 1970’s to prevent miscarriage.\\n• May still be sold over-the-counter in some countries.\\n• Although DES imposes no risks on the fetus, a high prevalence of breast cancer, cervical cancer, and vaginal cancer was found among daughters of women who have taken DES while pregnant.\\n• Antibiotics\\n• The quinolone family (ciprofloxacin and levofloxacin).\\n• Antibiotics.\\n• Available in the form of pills and injections.\\n• May cause toxicity in the joints or cartilage of fetuses and breastfed infants.\\n• Consult your physician if you are taking these medications or if you are in an urgent need to take them during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Chloramphenicol\\n• Antibiotic\\n• Available in the form of injections.\\n• May cause Gray baby syndrome in the newborn infant if taken during pregnancy.\\n• Consult your physician if you are taking these medications or if you need to take them during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Tetracycline\\n• Brand names: Doxypharm tab, Doxal caps, Sumycin, Terramycin, Tetracyn, Panmycin..\\n• Indications: Antibiotic.\\n• Available in the form of pills, syrup, and injections.\\n• Causes disorders in tooth and bone formations, birth defects, and liver toxicity. May result in tooth discoloration (brown, yellow, grey) and enamel atrophy if taken during the tooth formation period (the second half of pregnancy).\\n• Generally contraindicated during pregnancy, especially during the second half.\\n• Must consult a physician should there be a need to take this medication during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Psychiatric medications\\n• Barbiturates\\n• A wide group of drugs prescribed for multiple neurological diseases. Like Phenobarbitone (Luminal).\\n• Available in the form of pills and injections.\\n• Used in the treatment of multiple neurological disorders such as epilepsy and anxiety. It is also used as an anesthetic and in the treatment of acute migraine.\\n• Causes fetal malformations: heart malformations and hemorrhage, neural tube defects, cleft lip, and cleft palate. It may cause dependence in the fetus if taken during the third trimester of pregnancy. It may also cause a brain tumor in the fetus.\\n• Consult a physician should you need to take this medication during pregnancy or breastfeeding.\\n• Lithium\\n• Brand names: Lithium carbonate ER, Eskalith, and Lithobid. Lithonate\\n• Indications: Bipolar disease.\\n• Teratogenic effects: Ebstein’s anomaly (heart defects).\\n• Consult a physician should you need to use this medication during pregnancy.\\n• Contraindicated during breastfeeding.\\n•\n",
